          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex> be a smooth, connected, separated scheme, endowed with a base point <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[s\in  S]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f\colon  X\to  S]]></fr:tex> be a morphism of schemes such that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {R}^nf_*\mathbb {Q}]]></fr:tex> is a local system on <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[S]]></fr:tex>.
    Let <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex> be the Zariski closure of the image of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\pi _1(S,s)]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\operatorname {Aut}_\mathbb {C}((\mathrm {R}^nf_*\mathbb {C})_s)]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G^0]]></fr:tex> the identity component of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G]]></fr:tex>.
    Then:

    
 <html:ol xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(a) &quot;">
        If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[f]]></fr:tex> is smooth and proper, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G^0]]></fr:tex> is semi-simple.
      </html:li>

      
 <html:li style="list-style-type: &quot;(b) &quot;">
        In general, <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G^0]]></fr:tex> does not admit any quotient of multiplicative type (i.e. the radical of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[G^0]]></fr:tex> is unipotent).
      </html:li>

    </html:ol></fr:p>
  
    
